# .swarm-policy.md.example
#
# Copy this to the ROOT of a project as `.swarm-policy.md` to give the
# llm-dev-sandbox coordinator a per-project rules-of-engagement file.
# The coordinator reads it on every wake (Initial Startup Checklist step 1)
# and embeds it verbatim into every worker brief under a
# "## Project Guardrails (MUST OBEY)" header.
#
# Format: free-form markdown. The coordinator does not parse it; it just
# pastes the whole file into the worker brief. Be explicit and concrete.
# The worker (claude / gemini) reads it as part of its task and will refuse
# to violate clearly-stated rules in --yolo / --dangerously-skip-permissions
# mode (which otherwise has no other constraint).
#
# A baseline set of communication conventions (PR risk rating, end-of-work
# summary, decision-point framing, next-best-action hint, verbosity dial,
# "surface don't bury" notes) is ALREADY injected before this file via
# `prompts/worker-base.md`. You don't need to repeat them; only override
# in the "Communication overrides" section below if your project needs
# something different.

---

## Pull-request rules
- Workers may **only push branches**; never `merge`, `gh pr merge`, `git push origin master`, or anything that lands code on the default branch.
- PR titles must start with `[swarm]` so they're easy to filter in the UI.
- PR bodies must include the issue number being closed (`Closes #N`).
- Do not approve your own PR. Leave PRs in OPEN state for human review.

## File-modification rules
- Do **not** modify any of: `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`, `flyway/**`, `secrets/**`, `.env*`, `package-lock.json` (unless the task explicitly says so), `*.lock` (Gradle).
- Do **not** delete or rename files unless the task explicitly says so.
- Do **not** touch CI config (`.github/workflows/**`, `.gitlab-ci.yml`).

## Tool-use rules
- Do **not** run any `gradle` task matching `*release*`, `*publish*`, `*deploy*`.
- Do **not** run `kubectl`, `terraform`, `aws`, or any cloud CLI without explicit per-task approval.
- Database migrations are read-only research only — do not apply them.
- Network calls are fine for `gh`, `git`, `npm`, `pip`/`uv`, package registries; everything else is suspect.

## Concurrency rules
- Maximum 1 active worker per worktree.
- Do not spawn additional workers from inside a worker (no recursive provisioning).

## Communication rules
- If you (the worker) hit a real ambiguity that needs human input, **stop and ask in the pane**. Do not guess. Do not silently change scope.
- If the task is impossible as specified, write a short summary of why into `.agent-task-failed.md` and exit. Do not push a half-baked PR.
- Do not write any comments containing your model identifier or self-attribution unless explicitly asked.

## Communication overrides (optional)
This section overrides or extends the baseline conventions in
`prompts/worker-base.md` (which is injected above this file in every
worker brief). Use it for project-specific tuning. Examples of what could
go here:

- "Override default verbosity to `concise` for all workers in this repo."
- "PR risk rating must include a separate `<!-- LIQUIBASE_TOUCHED: yes|no -->` HTML comment when database migrations are present."
- "End-of-work summary must include a `## Coverage delta` section listing tests added/changed."
- "Next-best-action hints should always link to the project's runbook (`docs/RUNBOOK.md`) when CI fails."

Leave empty if the baseline is fine for this project.
